9 "§ 96A-2. Eligibility for benefits.
10 Beginning January 1, 2026, family and medical leave insurance benefits are payable to an
11 individual who:
12 (1) Meets the definition of "covered individual" as defined by G.S. 96A-1(b)(3);
13 and
14 (2) Meets one of the following requirements:
15 a. Because of birth, adoption, or placement through foster care, is caring
16 for a new child during the first year after the birth, adoption, or
17 placement of that child;
18 b. Is caring for a family member with a serious health condition;
19 c. Has a serious health condition;
20 d. Is caring for a covered service member who is the covered individual's
21 next of kin or other family member; or
22 e. Because of any "qualifying exigency leave" arising out of the fact that
23 the family member of the covered individual is on active duty (or has
24 been notified of an impending call or order to active duty) in the
25 Armed Forces.
26 "§ 96A-3. Duration of benefits.
27 (a) The maximum number of weeks during which family and medical leave insurance
28 benefits are payable under G.S. 96A-2(2)c. in an application year is 18 weeks.
29 (b) The maximum number of weeks during which family and medical leave insurance
30 benefits are payable under G.S. 96A-2(2)a., (2)b., or (2)e. in an application year is 12 weeks.
31 (c) The maximum number of weeks during which family and medical leave insurance
32 benefits are payable under G.S. 96A-2(2)d. in an application year is 26 weeks.
33 (d) The first payment of benefits must be made to an individual within two weeks after
34 the claim is filed, and subsequent payments must be made every two weeks thereafter.
35 "§ 96A-4. Amount of benefits.
36 (a) The amount of family and medical leave insurance benefits shall be determined as
37 follows:
38 (1) The weekly benefit shall be determined as follows: (i) the portion of the
39 covered individual's average weekly wage that is equal to or less than one
40 hundred percent (100%) of the State average weekly wage shall be replaced
41 at a rate of ninety percent (90%) and (ii) the portion of an employee's or
42 self-employed individual's average weekly wage that is more than one
43 hundred percent (100%) of the State average weekly wage shall be replaced
44 at a rate of fifty percent (50%).
45 (2) The maximum benefit shall be one hundred percent (100%) of the statewide
46 average weekly wage.
47 (3) The minimum weekly benefit shall not be less than one hundred dollars
48 ($100.00) per week except that if the covered individual's average weekly
49 wage is less than one hundred dollars ($100.00) per week, the weekly benefit
50 shall be the employee's full wage.
