1 (4) For purposes of this section, a covered individual's average weekly wage shall
2 be the average weekly wage during the 12 months preceding submission of
3 the application (or the average weekly wage during the time the covered
4 individual worked, if it was less than 12 months).
5 (b) Family and medical leave insurance benefits are not payable for less than eight hours
6 of family and medical leave taken in one workweek.
7 "§ 96A-5. Contributions.
8 (a) Payroll contributions shall be authorized in order to finance the payment of benefits
9 under the family and medical leave insurance program.
10 (b) Beginning on January 1, 2026, for each employee, an employer shall remit to the Paid
11 Family and Medical Leave Fund (Fund), established under G.S. 96A-16, contributions in the
12 form and manner determined by the Division. Annually, not later than October 1, the Assistant
13 Secretary shall fix the contribution rate for the coming calendar year in the manner described in
14 this subsection. For calendar years 2026 and 2027, the Assistant Secretary shall do so based on
15 sound actuarial principles. For calendar year 2028 and thereafter, the Assistant Secretary shall
16 first certify and publish the following information:
17 (1) The total amount of family and medical leave insurance benefits paid by the
18 Division during the previous fiscal year;
19 (2) The total amount remaining in the Fund at the close of the fiscal year;
20 (3) The total amount equal to one hundred forty percent (140%) of the previous
21 fiscal year's expenditure for family and medical leave insurance benefits paid
22 and for the administration of the family and medical leave insurance program;
23 (4) The amount by which the total amount remaining in the Fund at the close of
24 the previous fiscal year is less than or greater than one hundred forty percent
25 (140%) of the previous fiscal year's expenditure for family and medical leave
26 insurance benefits paid and for the administration of the family and medical
27 leave insurance program; and
28 (5) The amount by which the contribution rate shall be adjusted to ensure that the
29 Fund shall maintain or achieve an annualized amount of not less than one
30 hundred forty percent (140%) of the previous fiscal year's expenditure for
31 family and medical leave insurance benefits paid and for the administration of
32 the family and medical leave insurance program. The contribution rate
33 adjustment, if any, made as the result of the Assistant Secretary's certification
34 and report under this subsection shall supersede the rate previously set forth
35 and shall become effective on January 1 of the following calendar year.
36 (c) A self-employed individual who is electing coverage under G.S. 96A-13 shall be
37 responsible for the employee's share of contributions set forth in subsection (b) of this section on
38 that individual's income from self-employment.
39 (d) An employer shall not deduct more than fifty percent (50%) of the contribution
40 required for an employee by subsection (b) of this section from that employee's wages and shall
41 remit the full contribution required under said subsection to the Fund.
42 "§ 96A-6. Reduced leave schedule.
43 (a) A covered individual shall be entitled, at the option of the covered individual, to take
44 paid family and medical leave on an intermittent or reduced leave schedule in which all of the
45 leave authorized under this Chapter is not taken sequentially. Family and medical leave insurance
46 benefits for intermittent or reduced leave schedules shall be prorated.
47 (b) The covered individual shall make a reasonable effort to schedule paid family and
48 medical leave under this section so as not to unduly disrupt the operations of the employer. The
49 covered individual shall provide the employer with prior notice of the schedule on which the
50 covered individual will take the leave, to the extent practicable. Paid family and medical leave
